<root BTCPP_format="4" main_tree_to_execute="LockTargetXYTest">
    <!--
        Geometry-check + tuning harness for LockTargetXY. Calls the leaf DIRECTLY
        (not via a subtree) so every knob is settable here and the mission
        SUCCESS/FAILURE reflects whether the world-frame lock actually converged
        (no AlwaysSuccess mask), mirroring center_camera_test_mission.xml.

        Primary use is the Task 2 acceptance check: the sub starts off-centre
        over the table (see RelativeMove below), so the node logs
            LockTargetXY: err=.. m world(x,y) goal(x,y)
        The estimated world(x,y) must land on the table's ground-truth XY and,
        crucially, stay INVARIANT as the sub moves — a drifting estimate means a
        wrong cam_right/cam_down/cam_forward basis. A mirrored estimate means a
        sign flip on the offending axis. err is the metres between the gripper and
        the estimated target — the world-frame success residual — and should fall
        toward tol_world as the sub closes in.

        table_z is the table-top world z the pixel ray is cast onto (NOT the
        table model origin). Budget is ROS time (RosTimeout), so a slow-RTF sim
        run gets the intended sim-seconds. Run:
            ros2 launch subjugator_bringup task5_sim.launch.py stage:=LockTargetXYTest

        The RelativeMove first is REQUIRED, not incidental: robosub_2025.world
        spawns sub9 at (-7.702, 13.972) and the table sits at (-7.25, 14.0) — a
        delta of exactly the down_cam mount offset, i.e. the camera starts dead
        centre over the table. Backing off -0.35 m in body x puts the table
        off-centre at a known lateral offset with the whole table still in frame,
        so the projection actually runs and logs a world estimate to check.

        gripper_x/gripper_y are the REAL sub9.urdf.xacro gripper mount
        (xyz="0.354 0 -0.225"), not the node's 0,0 default, so this exercises the
        intended grasp configuration.
    -->
    <BehaviorTree ID="LockTargetXYTest">
        <Sequence>
            <!-- Introduce the known lateral offset the check needs. -->
            <SubTree ID="RelativeMove" _autoremap="true"
                     x="-0.35" y="0.0" z="0.0"
                     roll_deg="0.0" pitch_deg="0.0" yaw_deg="0.0"
                     pos_tol="0.10" ori_tol_deg="12.0" msec="20000"
                     ctx="{ctx}"/>

            <RosTimeout msec="10000" ctx="{ctx}">
                <Action ID="LockTargetXY"
                        camera="down"
                        label="table"
                        table_z="-0.85"
                        tol_world="0.05"
                        est_stable_tol="0.02"
                        settle_ticks="3"
                        miss_frames="5"
                        gripper_x="0.354"
                        gripper_y="0.0"
                        ema_alpha="0.3"
                        max_step="0.25"
                        ctx="{ctx}"/>
            </RosTimeout>
        </Sequence>
    </BehaviorTree>

    <!--
        Static geometry READ (no controller). Runs the leaf alone with max_step=0
        so nothing is commanded; the sub stays wherever it is teleported and the
        node just logs `err=.. world(x,y)` each fresh frame. This is the basis /
        projection validation: teleport the sub to a known off-centre pose over
        the table with the controller OFF, and confirm world(x,y) recovers the
        target's true world XY within ~5 cm.

        Target is a PROP (bandaid_box), not the table: a small object's bbox
        centre coincides with its true world XY, whereas the large table is
        usually only partly in frame so its bbox centre sits off the model origin
        by ~10 cm -- fine for S2 hovering, but useless as a geometry ruler.
        bandaid_box sits at world (-7.37, 14.09, ~-0.83). With the sub teleported
        to base (-8.05, 13.97, -0.13) the measured basis
        (cam_right=0,-1,0 cam_down=-1,0,0) lands world(x,y) within a few cm.
            ros2 run mission_planner mission_planner_node --ros-args \
                -p mission:=LockTargetXYStatic -p use_sim_time:=true \
                -r /down_camera/rgb/image_raw:=/down_cam/image_raw
    -->
    <BehaviorTree ID="LockTargetXYStatic">
        <RosTimeout msec="20000" ctx="{ctx}">
            <Action ID="LockTargetXY"
                    camera="down"
                    label="bandaid_box"
                    table_z="-0.80"
                    tol_world="0.05"
                    est_stable_tol="0.02"
                    settle_ticks="3"
                    miss_frames="5"
                    gripper_x="0.354"
                    gripper_y="0.0"
                    ema_alpha="0.3"
                    max_step="0.0"
                    ctx="{ctx}"/>
        </RosTimeout>
    </BehaviorTree>

    <!--
        MOTION grasp test using LockTargetXY for centering (competition Task 5).
        Mirrors ApproachAndGrasp but swaps step 1's HoneOverTarget (CenterCamera,
        camera-centering) for LockTargetXY (world-frame, GRIPPER-centering), which
        is the whole point: it drives the base so the gripper -- not the camera --
        ends over the target, folding in the 10 cm cam->gripper offset. Kept as a
        separate tree so the shared ApproachAndGrasp (used by the full mission +4
        others) is untouched while we evaluate.

        Target: bandaid_box (reliably detected from the hover pose; electric_box,
        the default grasp_target, is often out of frame). Centering degrades to
        dead-reckon on timeout via the Fallback, like HoneOverTarget.

        REQUIRES the controller. Safe bring-up order to avoid the stale-setpoint
        fling: start THIS mission with the controller OFF (LockTargetXY then
        streams a sane /goal_pose near current), and only then enable the
        controller so it follows that goal instead of a zero default.
            ros2 run mission_planner mission_planner_node --ros-args \
                -p mission:=LockGraspTest -p use_sim_time:=true \
                -r /down_camera/rgb/image_raw:=/down_cam/image_raw
            # then: ros2 service call /pid_controller/enable std_srvs/srv/SetBool "{data: true}"
    -->
    <BehaviorTree ID="LockGraspTest">
        <Sequence>
            <SetBlackboard output_key="target_label" value="bandaid_box"/>
            <RetryUntilSuccessful num_attempts="2">
                <Sequence name="grasp_cycle">
                    <!-- 1. Center the GRIPPER over the target (world-frame lock).
                         table_z is the object's detected-centre world z: bandaid_box
                         actually sits at gz z=-0.91 (the world-file -0.80 is the visual
                         pose, not the settled model origin). A too-shallow plane biases
                         the estimate toward the camera so it drifts under motion. -->
                    <Fallback>
                        <RosTimeout msec="40000" ctx="{ctx}">
                            <Action ID="LockTargetXY"
                                    label="{target_label}" camera="down"
                                    table_z="-0.83" tol_world="0.05" est_stable_tol="0.02"
                                    settle_ticks="3" miss_frames="5"
                                    gripper_x="0.354" gripper_y="0.0"
                                    ema_alpha="0.3" max_step="0.25"
                                    ctx="{ctx}"/>
                        </RosTimeout>
                        <AlwaysSuccess/>
                    </Fallback>
                    <!-- 2. Open gripper before descending -->
                    <Action ID="ActuateServo" target="gripper" angle="85" ctx="{ctx}"/>
                    <!-- 3. Dead-reckon descent to grasp depth -->
                    <SubTree ID="RelativeMove" _autoremap="true"
                             z="-0.45" pos_tol="0.2" ori_tol_deg="180.0"
                             msec="30000" ctx="{ctx}"/>
                    <!-- 4. Close to grasp, let the attach settle -->
                    <Action ID="ActuateServo" target="gripper" angle="0" ctx="{ctx}"/>
                    <RosDelay delay_msec="1500" ctx="{ctx}"><AlwaysSuccess/></RosDelay>
                    <!-- 5. Lift clear of the table -->
                    <SubTree ID="RelativeMove" _autoremap="true"
                             z="0.45" pos_tol="0.2" ori_tol_deg="180.0"
                             msec="30000" ctx="{ctx}"/>
                </Sequence>
            </RetryUntilSuccessful>
        </Sequence>
    </BehaviorTree>
</root>
